### Sorting Arrays in C#

C# provides multiple ways to sort arrays based on your needs.

### Array.Sort()

Sorts an array in place using the default comparer:

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 5, 2, 8, 1, 9 };
Array.Sort(numbers);  // { 1, 2, 5, 8, 9 }
```

### Array.Sort() with Custom Comparer

```csharp
// Descending order
Array.Sort(numbers, (a, b) => b.CompareTo(a));

// Sort by last character
string[] words = { "apple", "banana", "cherry" };
Array.Sort(words, (x, y) => x[^1].CompareTo(y[^1]));
```

### Sorting Part of an Array

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2 };
Array.Sort(numbers, 2, 3);  // Sort index 2-4 only
```

### LINQ Sorting

LINQ provides sorting without modifying the original array:

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 5, 2, 8, 1, 9 };

// Ascending
var sorted = numbers.OrderBy(n => n);

// Descending
var sortedDesc = numbers.OrderByDescending(n => n);

// Custom key
var byLastChar = words.OrderBy(w => w[^1]);
```

### Sorting with IComparer

```csharp
class LengthComparer : IComparer<string>
{
    public int Compare(string? x, string? y)
    {
        if (x == null || y == null) return 0;
        return x.Length.CompareTo(y.Length);
    }
}

Array.Sort(words, new LengthComparer());
```

### Sorting by Multiple Criteria

```csharp
var people = new (string Name, int Age)[]
{
    ("Alice", 30),
    ("Bob", 25),
    ("Charlie", 30)
};

var sorted = people
    .OrderBy(p => p.Age)
    .ThenBy(p => p.Name);
```

### Sort Methods Comparison

| Method | Modifies Original | Returns New | Use Case |
|--------|------------------|-------------|----------|
| `Array.Sort()` | Yes | No | In-place sorting |
| `Enumerable.OrderBy()` | No | Yes | LINQ queries |
| `List.Sort()` | Yes | No | List<T> sorting |

### Sorting Custom Types

```csharp
public class Person : IComparable<Person>
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }

    public int CompareTo(Person? other)
    {
        return Age.CompareTo(other?.Age);
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** `Array.Sort()` modifies the original array. LINQ's `OrderBy()` returns a new sequence without modifying the original. Use `OrderBy()` followed by `ThenBy()` for multi-criteria sorting.

codeExample:
using System;
using System.Linq;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        int[] numbers = { 9, 3, 7, 1, 6, 4, 8, 2, 5 };

        // In-place sort
        int[] sortedCopy = numbers.OrderBy(n => n).ToArray();
        Console.WriteLine("Original: " + string.Join(", ", numbers));
        Console.WriteLine("Sorted: " + string.Join(", ", sortedCopy));

        // Descending
        var descending = numbers.OrderByDescending(n => n);
        Console.WriteLine("Descending: " + string.Join(", ", descending));
    }
}
